n Birmingham; and a destitution service for asylum seekers in a city on the South coast, as well as in courts and advice agencies up and down the country. The authors argue that a failure to access justice all too often represents a catastrophic step in the life of the person concerned and their family. This powerful, yet moving, account humanises the hostile political debates that surround legal aid and reveals what access to justice really means in Austerity Britain.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aJustice, Administration ofzEngland. 0aJustice, Administration ofzGreat Britain. 0aJustice, Administration ofzWales. 0aLegal aidzEngland. 0aLegal aidzGreat BritainxFinance. 0aLegal aidzGreat Britain. 0aLegal aidzWales. 0aLegal assistance to the poorzEngland. 0aLegal assistance to the poorzGreat Britain. 0aLegal assistance to the poorzWales. 0aPublic welfarexLaw and legislationzGreat Britain. 7aLAW / Civil Law.2bisacsh1 aChakrabarti, Baroness Shami, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNewman, Daniel, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBristol UP/Policy Press Complete eBook-Package 2021z9783111196756oZDB-23-BUPP0 cprintz978152921312640uhttps://doi.org/10.56687/9781529213157?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781529213157423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781529213157/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-BUPPb2021